==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*mēlo-'', from Indo-European ''*mē-'' ‘to measure’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[mel|mēl]], Old Saxon ''-māl'' (Dutch [[maal]]), Old High German [[mal|māl]] (German [[Mal]] ‘time’, [[Mahl]] ‘meal’), Old Norse [[mál]], Gothic [[𐌼𐌴𐌻]] ‘time, hour’.  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[μετρον]], Latin [[mensus]], Russian [[мера]], Lithuanian [[metas|mẽtas]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /mæ:l/

===Noun===
'''mǣl''' ''n''
# a [[measure]]
#:''Do wines þrie mel on'': pour on three measures of wine.  (Leechbook)
# a [[mark]] or [[sign]], especially a [[cross]]
#:''Her oþiewde read Cristes mæl on hefenum'': in this year a red Christ's-sign appeared in the sky.  (''AS Chronicle'')
# a [[time]] or [[occasion]], a [[season]]
#:''Mæl is me to feran'': it is time for me to go.  (''Beowulf'')
# the time for eating, meal-time, a [[meal]]
#:''He gereordade æt anum mæle fif þusend manna'': at one meal he fed five thousand men.  (Wulfstan)

